# HONEST VERDICT
==================================================================
NNAPI / Edge TPU wins HARD on quantized classifiers that fit cleanly
into NNAPI semantics: mobilenet_v1_int8 = 10.5x speedup,
efficientnet_lite0_int8 = 2.5x, efficientnet_lite0_fp32 (driver fp16
path) = 5.0x. The Edge TPU is definitely hit: the benchmark log prints
"NNAPI accelerators available: [google-edgetpu,nnapi-reference]" and
the selected accelerator "google-edgetpu" returns sub-millisecond
conv kernels, and the full graph is delegated (31/31 for mobilenet, 1
partition, 1 delegate kernel).

It loses on detectors in three different ways.
(a) TFLite_Detection_PostProcess (standard in efficientdet/ssd exports)
is a custom op that NNAPI will not compile — the entire graph is
rejected and the nnapi-reference cpu fallback is ~60x slower than
XNNPack, so "--use_nnapi=true" on these models is strictly worse than
plain CPU.
(b) YOLOv8 as exported by SpotLab contains ops (likely Split / reshape
combinations the TPU firmware refuses) and ALSO hits
ANEURALNETWORKS_OP_FAILED — CPU wins by default.
(c) YOLO-FastestV2 converted via onnx2tf goes through *partially*
(176/218 ops delegated) but splits into 28 partitions / 14 delegate
kernels. The per-partition switch cost dominates and the result is
2x slower than XNNPack CPU. This is the expected fragmentation
failure mode Google documents for NNAPI.

So: for the robot's eyes pipeline, NNAPI + Edge TPU is the right
lever for classifiers / embeddings / simple backbones, but YOLO-style
detectors need either (i) int8 quantization with the postproc op
surgically removed and done on CPU, or (ii) replacing YOLO with a
lighter classifier / feature extractor to keep inference on the TPU.
The "acceleration column" finally has a tick for NNAPI: quantized
mobilenet-class models go from ~11 ms to ~1 ms on device.  We had
that ticked previously only for Vulkan, where everything lost.


