TFLite-CPU whisper-tiny.en (full graph) = 323.8 ms for a full transcription pass on a 30s-mel slot
  -> ~90x real-time on CPU alone.  Note the TFLite port uses greedy decode + forced_decoder_ids
  (no beam search), while whisper-cli uses beam=5 — that is the dominant difference,
  not TFLite vs ggml.

TFLite-CPU encoder only = 505.3 ms for a 30s-audio window.
whisper.cpp encoder only = 1261.9 ms for a 30s-audio window (actually 5s padded to 30s, same cost).
  -> TFLite/XNNPack encoder is 2.5x faster than whisper.cpp/ggml encoder on the same CPU,
     which mostly reflects XNNPack fp32 SIMD quality vs ggml's default fp16 path on Cortex-A76.

==========================================
# HONEST VERDICT: NNAPI / Edge TPU on Whisper Tiny @ Tensor G1
==========================================
NNAPI is NOT a win for Whisper Tiny on Pixel 6. Three distinct failure modes,
none of them fixable without re-architecting the model:

 1. FULL graph (encoder + autoregressive decoder) — NNAPI delegate rejects
    the model before op partitioning even starts, because the decoder's
    KV-cache tensor (#704) is dynamic-sized and NNAPI only supports static
    shapes.  0 ops delegated.  To put this on the Edge TPU at all you would
    have to export the decoder as a fixed-length loop (pad to N=448 every
    step) OR split encoder / decoder / cross-attn into separate TFLite
    files and orchestrate them from host code.  Both are multi-day work,
    not a 30-min port.

 2. ENCODER ONLY (static [1,80,3000] -> [1,1500,384]) — NNAPI accepts 228/
    262 ops but fragments them into 18 partitions.  The Edge TPU driver
    returns ANEURALNETWORKS_MISSED_DEADLINE_TRANSIENT (a compile-time
    timeout), Restored-original-execution-plan fallback fires, every op
    runs on CPU.  Same failure mode as YOLO-FastestV2 earlier in this file:
    a transformer encoder has reshape-heavy attention blocks that the Edge
    TPU firmware won't fuse, every attention layer is at least one boundary
    the TPU can't cross.  Capping partitions makes it worse (fewer delegated
    ops, still fragmented).  The partial-Erf rewrite is not the problem;
    simpler Conv-only chunks still break.

 3. Even if (2) compiled, partitioned transformers lose on NNAPI on this
    SoC — we saw exactly that on YOLO-FastestV2 in this same log (0.5x,
    CPU wins 2x because per-partition switch cost > gain).

Directional call: on Tensor G1 the Edge TPU is a win for single-stream
quantized CNN classifiers (MobileNet 10x, EfficientNet 2-5x) and is a
wash-to-negative for anything transformer-heavy or with dynamic shapes.
Whisper Tiny on-device on Pixel 6 should stay on whichever CPU path is
fastest — and that is XNNPack/TFLite (fp32 encoder = 505 ms @ 30s audio
= ~60x real-time on one window) NOT whisper.cpp/ggml (encode = 1262 ms
same window).  If the user-facing product is a voice interface on Pixel
6, the right move is to swap the whisper.cpp runtime for a TFLite+XNNPack
runtime — that alone is a 2.5x encoder speedup on CPU — and stop
chasing NNAPI for Whisper on this chip.

